AGI - 100 days after the opening of Paris 2024 and on the eve of the ignition of the Olympic flame in Athens, President Emmanuel Macron symbolically launches the countdown of the awaited international sporting event that sees France, the organizing country, in the front line. In a long speech to the television broadcaster Bfmtv and radio Rmc, the French president launched an appeal to the "Olympic Truce", respect, tolerance by athletes, giving a series of guarantees regarding safety.
&nbsp;
The Olympic Games will be held - from 26 July to 11 August - in an international context of great instability for different armed conflicts and geopolitical tensions in the Middle East and Europe. In addition to the threat of jihadist terrorism that stretches over the French sporting event, it is concrete the risk of strikes already induced by the Oltralpe unions to pressure the government on some reforms on the table. "We want to show the best face of France and we want the ceremony to be as successful as possible. It's a world premiere. We can do it and we will. We gave the means to do so, it is worth it" Macron began, promising a great opening and closing ceremony for the Paralympic Games.
&nbsp;
"Our country was hit by terrorism and what terrorists want is to stop us from dreaming. We're organizing, we're resisting. There is no naivety," the French President continued. In response to this threat, Macron confirmed the existence of "repletion scenes, B and C plans", as a ceremony limited to the Trocadero or a return to the French Stade, as well as an exceptional police mobilization, traffic limitation, security perimeters a week earlier.
&nbsp;
In reference to geopolitical conflicts, which in some way could have repercussions on the sports competition, the owner of the Elysée committed to "do everything possible to have an Olympic truce, to silence the weapons to negotiate". In his speech, Macron underlined the importance of "respect and tolerance" between opponents, who "are not enemies", stating that the athletes of Russia and Israel will be present and have nothing to do with the ongoing conflicts, therefore "it should not be made political" in that context.
&nbsp;
At the heart of the event there is sport: in a France presented by the president as a "sports nation", he listed all the positive aspects that revolve around, citing the values of respect, tolerance, his educational and health virtues, self-confidence. The stated goal is that of "sport for all, especially at school, since the elementary school, which must not be an accessory".
&nbsp;
As for the results of the Olympics, Macron set an ambitious goal for French athletes: enter the top 5 with 80 medals to conquer, and in the top 8 paralympics - from August 28 to September 8 - with about 40-50 medals. He then recognized a point of logistical weakness in the organization of the Olympic Games regarding access for disabled people to the Paris metro.
&nbsp;
"We have a strength and weakness. We have one of the most dense metropolitan networks in the world. Our weakness is that it is one of the oldest. We are not entirely up to and in line with the objectives in terms of accessibility standards. The reasons are multiple. We evaluated everything. The cost of a complete transformation of the subway was unsustainable," said Macron. Taxis will be available for people with reduced mobility during the Olympic Games.
&nbsp;
On the chapter of the many controversies that emerged in recent weeks, including the participation in the ceremony of the Maltese singer Francophone, Aya Nakamura, who triggered racist reactions of the extreme right, the French president responded that they were "slucking", promising instead a "full show with many French artists, international artists, opera singers, and with Aya Nakamura who, I hope, is present in the list". Personally, Macron will be present in Marseille on May 8 to welcome the Olympic flame, "but I do not think it is my place or my role to bring it. We'll see if anyone invites me to take her, but I'm not in the program." Instead, with regard to the commitment of the French president to bathe in the Seine, he replied that "I have not changed my mind. I'll be on the spot before July 26th."
&nbsp;
At stake there is the legacy of the Olympics with, insisted Macron, a series of structures and infrastructures that will be used later, the result of a long work launched in 2016. "When we talk about inheritance, the Seine and Marna will be one of the greatest heritage of these Olympic Games. was spent more than a billion euros. And not just for diving. In these areas we will have centers for water sports, which are very close to me for young people. 60% of the children of Seine-Saint-Denis cannot swim," concluded Macron.&nbsp;

