AGI - "The Middle East is on the brink of the barter." Thus i<span> the UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres warned the international community about the aggravation of the conflict, addressing the Security Council at a meeting on Iran's weekend attack on Israel. "No region or world can afford other wars," said Guterres.</span>
&nbsp;
"The peoples of the region are facing the real danger of a devastating large-scale conflict. Now it's time to disconnect and damp tensions," he added, inviting the "maximum moderation".<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
In the late Saturday night, Iran launched a direct attack on its acerrimous enemy of all time, Israel, launching a wave of over 300 missiles and drones. Almost all were intercepted by Israel and other countries, including the United States, Jordan and Great Britain. According to the Israeli army, 12 people were injured.
Iran declared that it had attacked in response to a deadly air attack on 1 April against the building of the consulate of Tehran in the Syrian capital Damascus, which was widely blamed by Israel. The attack killed seven Iranian Revolutionary Guards, including two high generals, and caused threats of retaliation by Iran.
The unprecedented exchange, which marks an important escalation between the two countries, has sparked new fears of a wider conflict, including the possibility of a counterattack by Israel.
&nbsp;
The United States has stated that they will not join any Israeli counterattack against Iran, while President Joe Biden warned Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to "reflect carefully" on any escalation hypothesis.
&nbsp;
The increasing tensions are part of the six-month Israeli war against Hamas in Gaza, which began after the unprecedented attack of the Palestinian militant group in Israel on October 7, which caused the death of 1,170 people, mostly civilians, according to an Israeli-based AFP count.
Israel's offensive of reprisal killed at least 33.729 people in Gaza, especially women and children, according to the Ministry of Health of the territory managed by Hamas.
&nbsp;
Since the beginning of the conflict, groups supported by Iran in Iraq, Lebanon, Syria and Yemen have made a burst of attacks against Israeli and Western goals.
On Sunday's Security Council meeting on the crisis took place at the request of Israel, whose ambassador Gilad Erdan urged the Council to "act (e) condemn Iran for its terrorism". The body must "impose all possible sanctions to Iran before it is too late", he said.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Iranian envoy to the United Nations Amir Saeid Iravani insisted that the Islamic Republic is exercising its "intrinsic right to self-defense".
"The Security Council... has failed to maintain international peace and security," said Iravani.
Therefore, Tehran "had no choice" except to answer, adding that his country "does not seek escalation or war", but will respond to any "threat or aggression".
&nbsp;
During his speech, Guterres reiterated his condemnation of Iranian attacks on Israel and the Israeli attack on the Iranian consulate in Damascus. "It's time to take a step back from the edge of the barter. It is essential to avoid any action that could lead to large military clashes on multiple fronts in the Middle East," said Guterres reiterated his appeal to &nbsp; "immediately ceased humanitarian fire" in Gaza, which according to experts is on the brink of famine.

