AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; Unidentified armed men killed the social leader Jaime Vasquez on Sunday in the Colombian city of Cucuta, which has the main border crossing with Venezuela and is located in the northeast of the country. William Villamizar, governor of the department of Nord de Santander, > whose capital is Cucuta, declared that the murder of Vasquez was perpetrated at 9:00 local time.
<br> "We have informed the authorities that we are offering a reward of 50 million pesos (about $13,000) to citizens who will provide information to clarify this situation and find the responsible," said Villamizar on social network X.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br The mayor of Cucuta, Jorge Acevedo, said "victim for the death of Jaime Vasquez", with whom he had a "constructive dialogue in recent years" and added in a post on X "I regret that his death occurred in my government because of a criminal and repugnant act". It hurts me that the voice of a civic defender, necessary in our democracy, in the Cucute of our soul, must be silenced. All my solidarity with his family, the entire population of Cucuta. Today is a sad day for all of us".<br> The police commander of Cucuta, Colonel William Quintero, explained that the crime was committed by two people: "a woman who maybe drove the bike (with whom the criminals fled) and the man who entered the premises (where the crime was committed) hitting the leader with a firearm."
<br Colombian President Gustavo Petro asked the Attorney General to conduct "the most in-depth investigations, which should include the forensic examination of information on his mobile phone, which apparently was manipulated by officials after his death."
